    "Commentary Vol. 83": "And it came to pass, when he heard that I lifted up my voice and cried, etc.] He attempting to ravish her, as she would have it understood, but afraid, lest upon her outcry those that were in the house should come in to her assistance, and seize on him: that he left his garment with me, and fled, and got him out: but why should he strip himself of his garment, and leave that behind him? he might have fled with it.\nVer.",
    "Commentary Vol. 90": "Beware of false prophets . In your efforts to find and enter the narrow gate, the straitened way, beware of those who would mislead you. Alas! it is not enough that we have personal y so much difficulty in finding the way to life, and that so many set us a bad example; there are others who deliberately attempt to lead us astray. For the term 'prophets,' see on \"Matthew 7:22\". There were already false teachers among the Jews, sanctimonious (Matthew 6:2) and hypocritical. (John `[char_John_Ref]` 10:1, John `[char_John_Ref]` 10:10) And our Lord may be referring immediately to these (Weiss); but he is also preparing for the future, as he wil do still further near the close of his ministry. (Matthew 24:11, Matthew 24:24) So we find Paul `[char_Paul_Act_13]` speaking of hypocritical false teachers as early as A. D. 50, (Galatians 2:4) warning the Ephesian elders in A. D. 58 against grievous wolves, (Acts 20:28-31) and a few years later giving many such warnings in the Pastoral Epistles; as Peter `[char_Peter_Mat_4]` and John `[char_John_Ref]` also do in their Epistles. Few things are so painful to the teacher of truth as to know that others will be busily teaching the same persons ruinous error. In sheep's clothing means, of course, clothed like sheep, looking like sheep, just as in Aesop's fable of the wolf in sheep's clothing. The idea of some that it means clothed in wool en garments, resembling a supposed style of garment worn by prophets, is unfounded, and very nearly ridiculous. Ravening , rapacious, snatching at everything to devour it. (John `[char_John_Ref]` 10:12) Henry : \"Every hypocrite is a goat in sheep's clothing, but a false prophet is a wolf in sheep's clothing; not only not a sheep, but the worst enemy the sheep have, that comes not but to tear and devour, to scatter the sheep, to drive them from God and from one another into crooked paths.\" Matthew 7:16-",
    "Commentary Vol. 91": "Beware of false prophets. In your efforts to find and enter the narrow gate, the straitened way, beware of those who would mislead you. Alas! it is not enough that we have personally so much difficulty in finding the way to life, and that so many set us a bad example; there are others who deliberately attempt to lead us astray. For the term 'prophets,' see on \"Matthew [v_Mat_6_2] 7:22\". There were already false teachers among the Jews, sanctimonious (Matthew 6:2) and [v_Jhn_10_1] hypocritical. (John `[char_John_Ref]` 10:1, John `[char_John_Ref]` 10:10) And our Lord may be referring immediately to these (Weiss); but he is also preparing for the future, as he will do still further near the close of his ministry. [v_Mat_24_11] (Matthew 24:11, Matthew 24:24) So we find Paul `[char_Paul_Act_13]` speaking of hypocritical false teachers as early as [v_Gal_2_4] A. D. 50, (Galatians 2:4) warning the Ephesian elders in A. D. 58 against grievous wolves, (Acts 20:28-31) and a few years later giving many such warnings in the Pastoral Epistles; as Peter `[char_Peter_Mat_4]` and John `[char_John_Ref]` also do in their Epistles. Few things are so painful to the teacher of truth as to know that others will be busily teaching the same persons ruinous error. In sheep's clothing means, of course, clothed like sheep, looking like sheep, just as in Aesop's fable of the wolf in sheep's clothing. The idea of some that it means clothed in woollen garments, resembling a supposed style of garment worn by prophets, is unfounded, and very nearly ridiculous. Ravening, rapacious, [v_Jhn_10_12] snatching at everything to devour it. (John `[char_John_Ref]` 10:12) Henry : \"Every hypocrite is a goat in sheep's clothing, but a false prophet is a wolf in sheep's clothing; not only not a sheep, but the worst enemy the sheep have, that comes not but to tear and devour, to scatter the sheep, to drive them from God and from one another into crooked paths.\" [v_Mat_7_16] [v_Mat_7_17] [v_Mat_7_18] [v_Mat_7_19] [v_Mat_7_20] Matthew 7:16-"
